## Mug Workspace

This is a Mug workspace. Write TypeScript using Mug's framework APIs.

### Framework APIs

**Connectors** ‚Äî sync external data and perform outbound actions (use `/connector` skill for guided setup):
- `import { source } from "@mugwork/mug"` ‚Äî read-only sync: `source({ name, database, tables: [{ name, primaryKey, fetch(ctx) }] })`
- `import { connector } from "@mugwork/mug"` ‚Äî bidirectional: `connector({ name, database, tables: [{ name, primaryKey, fetch(ctx), get(ctx, id), actions: { create(ctx, fields), update(ctx, id, fields), delete(ctx, id) } }] })`
- `ctx.credential(name?)` ‚Äî returns API key/token from workspace secrets
- Place connector files in `connectors/` ‚Äî auto-discovered by `mug deploy`
- Trigger sync: `curl -X POST http://localhost:8787/sync/my-api`

**AI** ‚Äî multi-provider with tier-based routing (use `/ai` skill for guided setup, `.mug/docs/ai.md` for full reference):
- `ctx.ai("fast", { prompt, system })` ‚Äî use workspace's fast model (cheapest). **You must set `prompt` (user message) and `system` (system prompt).**
- `ctx.ai("balanced", { prompt, system })` ‚Äî mid-tier model. `ctx.ai("powerful", { prompt, system })` ‚Äî strongest model.
- `ctx.ai("auto", { prompt, system })` ‚Äî Mug picks the tier based on prompt complexity
- `ctx.ai("provider/model", { prompt, system })` ‚Äî direct call: `"openai/gpt-5.4-nano"`, `"anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6"`
- Tiers configured in `mug.json` `ai.routing` (fast/balanced/powerful ‚Üí provider/model)
- **BYOK**: `mug secret set ai.anthropic=<key>` ‚Üí set `"ai.anthropic"` in `mug.json` `ai.billing` for unlimited AI at zero Mug credit cost
- Per-call billing: `billing: "ai.anthropic"` or `billing: "mug-metered"`. Per-workflow: `workflow(name, handler, { billing: "ai.anthropic" })`

**Search** ‚Äî find relevant data across synced sources:
- FTS5 auto-indexing: every synced text column gets a full-text index automatically. Query via `ctx.query(db, "SELECT * FROM {table}_fts WHERE {table}_fts MATCH ? ORDER BY rank", [keyword])`
- `ctx.search(query, { source?, limit? })` ‚Äî semantic similarity search. Returns `{ score, table, primaryKey, row }[]`. Requires deployed workspace (uses Vectorize).
- `ctx.ask(question, { source?, limit?, model?, system? })` ‚Äî full RAG: searches relevant data, feeds to LLM, returns grounded answer. Returns `{ answer, sources, usage }`.
- `ctx.embed(texts)` ‚Äî generate vector embeddings for an array of strings (batches of 100). Returns `number[][]`. Used internally by `ctx.search`, but available for custom similarity matching.
- Three layers: FTS5 for keyword search (free, local), `ctx.search()` for semantic (deployed), `ctx.ask()` for natural language answers (deployed).
- See `.mug/docs/api.md` for full signatures and `.mug/docs/ai.md` for when to use each layer.

**Workflows** ‚Äî multi-step automation (use `/workflow` skill for guided setup):
- `workflow(name, async (ctx) => { ... }, options?)` ‚Äî register a workflow. Options: `{ description?, schedule?: string | ScheduleConfig, billing?, webhook?: true | { auth, secret }, inbound?: "sms" | "email" | "slack", trigger?: { source, table?, on?, includeInitialSync? } }`
- **ScheduleConfig** ‚Äî `{ weekday?, nth? (1-5 or -1=last), time? ("HH:MM"), interval? ("15m"/"1h"), between? (["14:00","16:00"]), skipHolidays? (true or "US"), skipDates? (["YYYY-MM-DD"]), cron?, timezone? }`
- Every workflow must have a `description` in options. Add `//` comments above each `ctx.*` call and `return` ‚Äî these appear as step descriptions in the explorer.
- `ctx.query(database, sql, params?)` ‚Äî read from any workspace database
- `ctx.exec(database, sql, params?)` ‚Äî write to any workspace database
- `ctx.ai()` ‚Äî see **AI** section above
- `ctx.notify.email({ to, message, subject?, fromName?, cta? })` / `.sms({ to, message })` / `.slack({ to, message, blocks?, thread_ts? })` / `.channel(name, options)` for custom channels
- `ctx.surfaceUrl(surfaceId, path?)` ‚Äî generate URL to a surface (dev/prod-aware)
- `ctx.file(path)` ‚Äî read a file from `files/` as ArrayBuffer (R2 in prod, local in dev)
- `ctx.fileText(path)` ‚Äî read a file as UTF-8 string
- `ctx.secret(name)` ‚Äî read a workspace secret by name (from `.mug/secrets`). Throws if not found.
- `ctx.waitFor(eventName, options?)` ‚Äî pause workflow until an external event arrives. Returns `{ payload, type, timedOut }`. Options: `{ timeout?: "1 hour" | "24 hours", message?: string }`. Zero cost while waiting.
- `ctx.waitForUrl(eventName)` ‚Äî generate a one-time callback URL for embedding in notifications. Returns a URL that, when visited, sends the event to the waiting workflow.
- `ctx.http(url, options?)` ‚Äî outbound HTTP request. Returns `{ status, headers, body, json, ok }`. Throws on non-2xx by default (`throwOnError: false` to handle manually). Auto-retries connection errors and 429 with exponential backoff. Options: `{ method?, headers?, body?, throwOnError?, retry?: { attempts? } | false, timeout?, sign?: { secret, header? } }`
- `ctx.respond(body, status?)` ‚Äî set a custom HTTP response for webhook-triggered workflows. First call wins. Use for Slack challenge verification, Twilio TwiML, etc. If not called, webhook returns default `{ ok: true }`.
- `ctx.action(connectorName)` ‚Äî returns a handle for outbound operations: `.read(table, id)`, `.create(table, fields)`, `.update(table, id, fields)`, `.delete(table, id)`, `.upsert(table, id, fields)`. **Workflow-only** ‚Äî all external writes go through `ctx.action()`. Transforms auto-snapshot before writing (for rollback). Returns `ActionResult` with `{ connector, table, operation, recordId, data, snapshot, operationId }`.
- `ctx.rollback(actionId)` ‚Äî undo a prior action using its stored before-snapshot. Executes the inverse as a new action. `ctx.rollbackRun(workflowRunId)` rolls back all actions from a run in reverse order.
- `maxOperations` ‚Äî default 100 per workflow run. Override: `workflow(name, handler, { maxOperations: 500 })`. Counts all `ctx.action()` calls.
- Place workflow files in `workflows/` ‚Äî auto-discovered by `mug deploy`

**Notifications** ‚Äî email and SMS from workflows (use `/notify` skill for guided setup):
- `ctx.notify.email({ to, message, subject?, fromName?, cta?: { label, url } })` ‚Äî styled HTML email with optional CTA button
- `ctx.notify.sms({ to, message })` ‚Äî SMS via Twilio (E.164 format)
- `ctx.surfaceUrl("approvals")` ‚Äî returns correct URL for dev (`localhost:8787`) or prod (`workspace.mug.work`)
- In local dev, emails send via Resend (real delivery) + console log
- BYOK: set your own Resend/Twilio keys via `mug secret set` for unlimited sends
- **Usage limits**: email/SMS/AI have per-tier limits. `ctx.notify` and `ctx.ai` throw when limits are exceeded ‚Äî catch in workflows to handle gracefully. Enable overages at mug.work or `mug billing --overage <meter>=on` to allow per-unit billing beyond limits. BYOK bypasses metered limits. See `.mug/docs/billing.md` for tier details.

**Slack surface** ‚Äî send Block Kit messages, slash commands, interactive buttons, Home Tab (use `/slack` skill for guided setup):
- `ctx.notify.slack({ to, message, blocks?, thread_ts? })` ‚Äî send messages with raw Block Kit. `to` accepts `#channel-name`, `channel-name`, or channel ID. Names resolve automatically. Bot auto-joins public channels; private channels need manual invite via Integrations tab.
- `ctx.slack.updateMessage({ channel, ts, text?, blocks? })` ‚Äî update a message after an action (replace buttons with result)
- `ctx.slack.openModal({ triggerId, view })` ‚Äî open a modal from a slash command workflow
- Action ID convention: `mug:<workflow>:<action>` routes button clicks to specific workflows
- Slash command trigger: `"trigger": { "type": "slack_command", "command": "/dispatch" }` in workflow config
- Event trigger: `"trigger": { "type": "slack_event", "event": "message" }` in workflow config
- Slack data auto-synced: `slack_users` (user_id, email, display_name) and `slack_channels` (channel_id, name) tables
- Block Kit reference: agents already know Block Kit ‚Äî use it directly, no Mug abstraction layer
- `ctx.slackApiCall(method, body)` ‚Äî call any Slack Web API method directly (e.g., `reactions.add`, `pins.add`, `users.info`). Requires SLACK_BOT_TOKEN.
- Slack API docs (LLM-optimized): `https://docs.slack.dev/apis/web-api.md`
- **Agent DMs**: set `"chat": true` in agent.json + `"defaultAgent"` in slack.json ‚Üí threaded AI conversations via Slack's Agents & AI Apps. Multi-agent routing via suggested prompts and @mentions. See `.mug/docs/slack.md`.

**Inbound messages** ‚Äî receive SMS replies, email replies, Slack interactions:
- Configure in workflow options: `workflow("handle-sms", handler, { inbound: "sms" })`
- Webhook URLs shown after `mug deploy`: `https://api.mug.work/inbound/sms/<workspace>`, etc. Run `mug webhooks` to see all URLs.
- SMS workflow receives: `ctx.params = { channel: "sms", from: "+1...", body: "YES", messageSid: "SM..." }`
- Email workflow receives: `ctx.params = { channel: "email", from: "user@...", subject: "Re: ...", body: "..." }`
- Slack workflow receives: `ctx.params = { channel: "slack", userId: "U...", actionId: "approve_btn", actionValue: "..." }`
- **Pattern**: "send and wait for reply" uses two workflows ‚Äî one sends + sets a status field in DB, the other catches the inbound reply + checks that field to determine what to do

**Forms** ‚Äî collect data from users (use `/form` skill for guided setup):
- Config-driven JSON files in `surfaces/<name>.json` with `"type": "form"` ‚Äî form is live immediately in `mug dev`
- Field types: text, email, phone, number, select, multiselect, date, textarea, file, calculated, hidden
- **Field names must be unique across the entire form** (including across pages and showWhen fields) ‚Äî duplicates cause silent data loss. `mug form validate` catches this.
- Field properties: `default` (static value), `prefill` (from auth row, URL param, or DB), `locked` (read-only + server-enforced), `helpText` (hint below label), `validate` (custom rules with error messages)
- Validation + help text support `{{column}}` templates resolved from auth row (e.g., `helpText: "You have {{pto_hours}} hours available"`)
- Conditional fields: `showWhen: [{ field, op, value }]` (ops: eq, neq, in, gt, lt, filled, empty)
- Multi-page: `pages: [{ id, title, fields }]` with optional branching
- Access modes: `public` (anyone), `identify` (verify email/phone), `auth` (restricted to known users ‚Äî also provides auth row for prefill)
- Handler workflow receives submissions via `ctx.params`. Place handler in `workflows/handle-<name>.ts` ‚Äî auto-discovered.
- Auth prefill: `prefill: { source: "auth", column: "name" }` auto-fills from the user's auth row. Combine with `locked: true` for identity fields. Use `access.query` with `:identity` placeholder for computed columns (JOINs, calculations) ‚Äî no denormalized state needed.
- Dynamic forms: `ctx.collect(options)` creates forms programmatically at runtime (advanced ‚Äî see `.mug/docs/forms.md`)
- Breadcrumbs: add `?from=/portal&fromLabel=Back to Portal` to surface links ‚Äî target surface shows a back link above the header

**Portals** ‚Äî tabbed, section-based data pages (use `/portal` skill for guided setup):
- Config-driven JSON files in `surfaces/<name>.json` with `"type": "portal"`
- `tabs` ‚Äî array of tabs, each with `id`, `label`, and `sections` array. Single-tab portals hide the tab bar. Tab options: `color` (text/underline color), `countQuery` (dynamic badge count).
- Top-level `sections` on the config render above the tab bar and stay visible on all tabs. Stats items support `href` to make cards clickable links (e.g., `"href": "?tab=pending"`).
- Section types: `table` (paginated rows ‚Üí detail pages ‚Üí action buttons), `stats` (metric cards), `progress` (progress bars), `text` (markdown), `chart` (bar/donut SVG), `gallery` (image grid), `accordion` (collapsible container)
- Table sections have `query`, `columns`, `detail`, `actions`, `pageSize`. Use `:user` in SQL for session identity, `:auth.column` for any auth table column.
- Action button styles: `"success"` (green), `"danger"` (red), `"warning"` (amber), `"primary"` (accent), `"default"` (gray). Add `"color": "#hex"` for custom override. Use success/danger for approve/deny.
- Actions are **optimistic** ‚Äî button replaced instantly with status message. `afterMessage`: custom text (`{{timestamp}}` for date/time). `afterColor`: hex color for the status message. `afterActions`: follow-up buttons (e.g., revoke/undo) that fire the same workflow.
- **Timeline playback**: action buttons can trigger scripted visual sequences instead of workflows. Set `"timeline"` (array) instead of `"workflow"` (string). Events: `toast` (notification popup), `preview` (email/SMS card), `stream` (char-by-char AI-style text), `update` (swap table cell value), `highlight` (pulse-highlight row via `row` or button via `action`, with optional `message` badge). Each event has `delay` (seconds from trigger). Button disabled during playback.
- **Autoplay**: portal config accepts `"autoplay": []` ‚Äî same event array, fires on page load. Use for guided demos (`highlight` with `delay: 0`) or AI summary streams on dashboards.
- **Embed mode**: append `?embed=true` to any surface URL to strip header chrome (logo, session, logout, breadcrumbs) for iframe embedding. CSP allows framing from `mug.work` and `*.mug.work`.
- Stats `valueColor`: `"match"` (inherit border color ‚Äî default when `color` set), `"neutral"` (dark text), or hex. Badge `badgeColors`: `{ "PTO": "#3b82f6" }` for custom non-status values.
- Access modes: same as forms (`public`, `identify`, `auth`)
- Column `dateFormat`: `"short"` for compact dates (`5/15/26, 3:30 PM`). Default is long format (`May 15, 2026, 3:30 PM`).
- Column/field/stat formats: `"currency"` ($X,XXX.XX in tables, whole in stats), `"currency-whole"` ($X,XXX), `"currency-short"` ($12.5K/$1.2M), `"number"` (comma-separated), `"percent"` (XX%). Stat values that overflow auto-abbreviate to K/M.
- Chart sections: `labelColumn`/`valueColumn` default to `"label"`/`"value"`. `colors`: `{ "complete": "#16a34a", "error": "#ef4444" }` maps label values to colors.
- All `date`/`datetime` columns render in the workspace timezone (`settings.timezone` in mug.json). Override per-surface with `"timezone": "America/New_York"` in the surface JSON.

**Demo mode** ‚Äî share deployed auth'd surfaces with stakeholders without requiring them to verify:
- `mug demo enable <surface> --as <email-or-phone>` ‚Äî surface renders pre-authenticated as that identity
- Use `_home` as the surface ID to demo the workspace home screen (e.g. `mug demo enable _home --as demo@example.com`)
- `mug demo disable <surface>` / `mug demo status` ‚Äî manage active demos
- Notification routing (automatic, no code guards needed):
  - `--notify demo-user` (default) ‚Äî notifications redirect to `--as` identity (matching channels only, others suppressed)
  - `--notify dev` ‚Äî notifications redirect to the developer's account email
  - `--notify off` ‚Äî suppress all notifications (logged but not sent)
  - Per-channel overrides: `--email-to <addr>`, `--sms-to <phone>`, `--slack-to <channel>` (override any mode)
- `--no-workflows` ‚Äî suppress workflow execution entirely (surface still renders and accepts input)
- `ctx.isDemo` is `true` in demo workflows ‚Äî use to guard non-notification side effects (destructive writes, external API calls)
- Create a demo persona (e.g. `demo@example.com`) in your auth table with curated data. The demo viewer sees exactly what that user would see.

**Branding** ‚Äî custom logo and accent color on all surfaces and emails:
- Configure in `mug.json`: `"branding": { "logo": "assets/logo.png", "logoSquare": "assets/icon.png", "accentColor": "#1a5276", "ogImage": "assets/og-image.png" }`
- Two logo variants: `logo` (rectangle, for headers) and `logoSquare` (square, for icons). If only one provided, used everywhere.
- `ogImage` ‚Äî custom 1200x630 PNG for link previews (Slack, iMessage, LinkedIn, Discord). Falls back to Mug default if not set.
- Logo paths are relative to workspace root. Uploaded to R2 on `mug deploy`, served at `https://<workspace>.mug.work/_branding/`
- Accent color applies to buttons, links, focus rings, progress bars via CSS variable `--accent`. Also tints the browser favicon.
- All surfaces automatically emit Open Graph and Twitter Card meta tags (title, description, image) for link previews.
- Emails automatically use workspace branding (logo in header, accent on CTA buttons)
- **Per-surface overrides**: add `"branding": { "logoSquare": "files/logo.png", "accentColor": "#2563eb" }` to any surface JSON to override workspace branding for that surface. Surface branding takes precedence; workspace branding is the fallback.
- In dev, logos served from local files. Changes to mug.json branding hot-reload.

**Home Screen** ‚Äî workspace root URL (`subdomain.mug.work/`) shows branded auth + surface directory:
- By default, the home screen requires authentication ‚Äî visitors verify via email/phone before seeing content.
- **Public mode**: add `"access": { "mode": "public" }` to `_home.json` to show public surfaces without auth. Optional `"showLogin": true` adds a "Log in" button (only renders if at least one surface has non-public access).
- Auth is configless: scans workspace owner/admin + all surface auth tables. No setup needed.
- Auth flow: demo mode check ‚Üí session cookie check ‚Üí auth gate (email/phone verification).
- After login, shows a directory of surfaces the user has access to.
- Demo mode: `mug demo enable _home --as <identity>` ‚Äî the home screen is surface ID `_home` for demo purposes.
- Configure layout in `surfaces/_home.json`: `{ "title": "...", "description": "...", "groups": [...] }`
- `title` ‚Üí rendered as heading in header, page title, OG meta (fallback: title-cased workspace slug). `description` ‚Üí rendered below title in header + OG/Twitter meta.
- Groups combine a button row (actions) with card list (destinations):
  `{ "label": "HR", "description": "...", "icon": "users", "buttons": [{ "surface": "time-off", "label": "Request Time Off" }], "cards": [{ "surface": "portal", "label": "Dashboard", "description": "...", "icon": "layout-dashboard" }] }`
- Optional `color` on groups (tints border + bg + title + icons), buttons (bg override), cards (colored border + tint).
- Optional `icon` on groups and cards ‚Äî any [Lucide icon](https://lucide.dev) name (e.g., `"hard-hat"`, `"receipt"`, `"bar-chart-3"`).
- Optional `"collapsible": true` on groups ‚Äî renders as accordion. `"collapsed": true` starts closed (default: open).
- Named color palette: Red `#dc2626`, Orange `#ea580c`, Gold `#ca8a04`, Brown `#92400e`, Green `#16a34a`, Teal `#0f766e`, Blue `#2563eb`, Navy `#1e3a8a`, Purple `#7c3aed`, Pink `#db2777`, Maroon `#6b2140`, Gray `#475569`.
- Surfaces not in any group appear at the bottom as default cards.
- No `_home.json` = all surfaces shown alphabetically as cards.
- Uses workspace branding (logo, accent color, OG meta). Fully mobile responsive.
- In dev, `localhost:8787/` shows home screen with all surfaces and dev identity. Changes to `_home.json` hot-reload.

